    "body": "## Problem\r\n\r\nNeovim only supports one editing paradigm: verb-noun (operator-pending). You type `d3w` and hope you counted the words right. There's no way to see what you're about to operate on before committing to the action.\r\n\r\nEditors like Helix have demonstrated that noun-verb (selection-first) editing is a viable and often preferred alternative, you select first, see the selection highlighted, then apply the verb. But Helix lacks Neovim's plugin ecosystem, API, and extensibility. Users are forced to choose between the editing model they want and the editor they've invested in.\r\n\r\nThere is no clean way to implement this as a plugin. Selection-first editing requires intercepting motion handlers at the C level, before the normal mode state machine processes them. Lua-based attempts are fragile, laggy, and can't integrate with the rendering pipeline.\r\n\r\n## Solution\r\n\r\nAdd a global string option `paradigm` with two values: `'vim'` (default) and `'helix'`.\r\n\r\nWhen `paradigm=helix`, Normal mode becomes selection-first:\r\n\r\n- **Motions create selections.** `w`, `b`, `e`, `$`, `0`, `G`, `gg`, `{`, `}`, `/`, `?`, `n`, `N` select from the current position to the destination. Each motion creates a fresh selection (not cumulative).\r\n- **`h`/`j`/`k`/`l` navigate.** They move the cursor and select only the single character under it, pure navigation with a 1-char selection that operators can still act on.\r\n- **Verbs act on the selection.** `d`, `y`, `c`, `<`, `>` operate on whatever is currently selected, then collapse back to 1 char.\r\n- **`Esc` collapses** the selection without executing anything.\r\n- **`mode()` returns `'n'`.** Plugins see Normal mode. No compatibility issues.\r\n\r\n### Design decisions\r\n\r\n- **Zero impact when `paradigm=vim`.** Every behavioral change is gated behind `HELIX_MODE()`. The classic code paths are untouched.\r\n- **Not Visual mode.** The helix selection is a separate `HelixSelection` struct (`anchor`, `head`, `has_selection`, `inclusive`). It never sets `VIsual_active`, never triggers Visual mode autocmds, and uses its own highlight groups (`HelixCursor`, `HelixSelection`).\r\n- **Reuses existing operators.** `helix_apply_operator()` translates the selection into an `oparg_T` and calls `op_delete`, `op_yank`, etc. No operator logic was rewritten.\r\n- **Minimal rendering changes.** The helix selection rendering hooks into the existing `area_highlighting` path in `drawline.c`, following the same pattern as Visual mode highlighting.\r\n\r\n### Files changed\r\n\r\n| File | Change |\r\n|---|---|\r\n| `src/nvim/options.lua` | Declare `paradigm` option |\r\n| `src/nvim/option_vars.h` | `HELIX_MODE()` macro, `p_pdm` variable |\r\n| `src/nvim/state_defs.h` | `HelixSelection` struct |\r\n| `src/nvim/globals.h` | Global `current_helix_sel` |\r\n| `src/nvim/state.c` | Selection init/collapse/extend functions |\r\n| `src/nvim/normal.c` | Helix branches in motion and verb handlers |\r\n| `src/nvim/ops.c` | `helix_apply_operator()` dispatcher |\r\n| `src/nvim/drawline.c` | Selection highlight rendering |\r\n| `src/nvim/highlight_group.c` | Default highlight group definitions |\r\n\r\n### Usage\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nvim.opt.paradigm = 'helix'  -- selection-first\r\nvim.opt.paradigm = 'vim'    -- back to classic (default)\r\n```\r\n\r\nSwitchable at runtime, no restart needed.",
